<methods>
<methodStep>
<description>
<section>
<title>Experimental Design</title>
<para>Sites were established in recently burned and unburned evergreen stands across rocky uplands, silty uplands, and sandy lowlands to monitor the effects of fire on vegetation and soil thermal and moisture regimes.</para>
</section>
<section>
<title>Methods</title>
<para>Thaw depths were measured with a metal probe in late-August to mid-September.Soil pH and electrical conductivity were measured with hand-held meters. Soil samples were taken for bulk density and volumetric soil moisture, based on wet and oven-dried (60?C) weights. Water storage (equivalent depth) was calculated as the total water content in the active layer or seasonally frozen layer. The net heat input into the active layer during the thaw season was estimated as the sum of latent and sensible heat in mid-August, based on moisture contents, mineral and organic soil fractions, and temperature gradients of the active layer. Additional methodology for soil temperatures is found in the associated datasets.</para>
</section>
